This document is created to practice Git Commands in PowerShell. 

Steps:-

1. Open PowerShell window
2. Check the directory / folder for the project
3. Check whether Git is main / Branch - <git status>
4. Switch to main - <git switch main>
5. To create a new branch - <git branch branch_name>
6. check status of the branch created - <git status>
7. Switch to new branch created as we are now in main branch - <git switch new_branch_name>
8. check status - <git status>
9. To add & commit files to the new branch created - <git add . > and to commit <git commit -m "description to track commit" 
10. To Push these files to Git Repository - <git push>
(this gives a upstream, copy it)
11. Paste the above copied upstream < git push --set-upstream origin filename >
12. To check the changes in main first switch from branch to main - <git switch main>
13. Then create a pull request - <git pull>

14. Now login to GitHub
a. the new branch created is visible
b. then commit pull & merge branch to main

15. When any changes made to files 
a. check status - <git status>
b. add & commit - <git add . > and git commit -m "update description for Git tracking with filename"
c. then push these changes - <git push> (this gives an upstream to be copied)
d. copy the upstream and push - <  git push --set-upstream origin filename >
e. pull changes from branch to main in local repository <git pull>


